  headline="AI WhatsApp for UK Loft Conversion Specialist Companies"
  accentWord="Loft Conversion"
  subhead="A homeowner WhatsApps at 11:45am with four photos — the loft hatch from below, the inside of the loft showing the ridge and purlins, a tape measure stretched from joist to ridge reading 2.5 metres, and the chimney breast running through the centre of the space. Her message: 'Hi — thinking about a loft conversion. Here is what we have got to work with. 3-bed semi in OX3. Want a bedroom and en-suite. Is the chimney breast a problem? Are you free to survey?' You are on site at a dormer conversion in Carterton — the roofer is tiling the new dormer and you are checking the lead flashings against the detail drawings. Without AI WhatsApp, the message sits for four hours. She messages two more companies; one responds in eight minutes. With it, the AI replies instantly, acknowledges the photos, asks about the roof shape and party wall situation, and your lead — complete with loft measurements and chimney breast photos — arrives at lunchtime."
  scenario="It is 8:05am on a Saturday. A couple in Abingdon have been discussing a loft conversion for months. This morning they have decided: they want a hip-to-gable with a rear dormer to create the maximum space on their 1960s semi. He WhatsApps four loft conversion specialists from Google: 'Morning — we want a hip-to-gable and rear dormer loft conversion on our 3-bed semi in OX14. Currently hipped both sides. Want to create two bedrooms and a shower room. Ridge height is about 2.3m — bit tight but hoping hip-to-gable solves it. Have not applied for planning yet. Can you survey and advise on what is possible?' Without AI WhatsApp, you are still asleep. By 10am the couple have received two professional replies — one with a video explaining hip-to-gable benefits and an offer of a Monday survey. Your reply at 10:30 is third. With AI WhatsApp, the response arrives at 8:06am: 'Thank you — hip-to-gable conversions on 1960s semis are one of our most common projects. Converting the hipped roof to a gable typically adds the headroom needed for comfortable rooms. Could you send photos of the existing roof from outside, showing both hips? We will assess the conversion potential and arrange a survey.' He sends two exterior shots. Saturday at 10am you check your phone: hip-to-gable plus dormer, 3-bed 1960s semi, OX14, two bedrooms and shower room, 2.3m ridge, hipped both sides, exterior photos attached, no planning yet. You call and book a Tuesday evening survey — the earliest slot — and arrive with a clear understanding of the roof geometry."
  benefits={benefits}
